## Analysis

> #### Hypothesis

This analysis models daily **total steps** as a function of an individual’s daily **average heart rate**. Because patterns observed in 2023 appeared to differ from subsequent years, the data are partitioned using a binary indicator that distinguishes observations from 2023 from those occurring in 2024–2026. The regression model includes both this indicator and its interaction with heart rate, allowing the baseline level of steps and the heart rate–steps relationship in 2023 to differ from the pooled post-2023 period.

<!-- TeX commands taken from: https://byuistats.github.io/Statistics-Notebook/LinearRegression.html -->
$$
\underbrace{Y_i}_\text{Total Steps} \underbrace{=}_{\sim}
\overbrace{\beta_0}^{\stackrel{\text{y-int}}{\text{baseline}}} +
\overbrace{\beta_1}^{\stackrel{\text{slope}}{\text{baseline}}}
\underbrace{X_{1i}}_\text{Avg Heart Rate} +
\overbrace{\beta_2}^{\stackrel{\text{change
in}}{\text{y-int}}}  \underbrace{X_{2i}}_\text{1 if 2023} +
\overbrace{\beta_3}^{\stackrel{\text{change in}}{\text{slope}}}
\underbrace{X_{1i}X_{2i}}_\text{Interaction} + \epsilon_i
$$


If $\beta_2$ = 0, then at the same average heart rate, the expected number of daily steps is the same in 2023 and in the pooled post-2023 period. If $\beta_2$ \neq 0, then 2023 differs in its baseline level of activity. We'll use $\alpha = 0.05$.

$$
H_0: \beta_2 = 0 \text{ (Equal baseline daily steps for 2023 and 2024–2026)}\\  
H_a: \beta_2 \neq 0 \text{ (Different baseline daily steps in 2023 compared to 2024–2026)}\\
\alpha = 0.05
$$


We're testing whether the relationship between heart rate and steps differs between 2023 and the pooled post-2023 period. We'll use $\alpha = 0.05$.

$$
H_0:\ \beta_3 = 0 \quad \text{(Same heart rate:steps relationship in 2023 and 2024–2026)}\\
H_a:\ \beta_3 \neq 0 \quad \text{(Different heart rate:steps relationship in 2023)}
$$




