## Testing

> Two-Lines Model Summary

<!-- <strong style = "background: yellow;">From Brother Saunders:</strong> -->

<!-- - [x] Interpret the four *estimates* from the summary. -->
<!-- - [x] Include y-hat math formula. -->

Below we read from the *multiple linear regression model* summary:

<!-- NOTE: Brother Saunders told me how to change this from a SIMPLE to MULTIPLE linear regression -->
```{r}
# 1.1) Perform statistical test
mylm <- lm(Steps ~ HeartRate + is_2023 + HeartRate:is_2023, data = health)
mylm_summary <- summary(mylm)

# 1.2) Display test results
pander(mylm_summary)
```

**Mathematical Model:**

$$
\underbrace{\hat{Y}_i}_\text{Est. Total Steps} = \overbrace{`r round(mylm_summary$coef[1], 3)`}^\text{est. y-int} + \overbrace{`r round(mylm_summary$coef[2], 3)`}^\text{est. slope} \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Heart Rate}
$$



> Summary Interpretation

**(Intercept)**

* *Estimate* - The estimated number of daily steps for an observation not from 2023 when average heart rate is zero is −4,312. Because a heart rate of zero is physiologically impossible, the intercept is not meaningful in a practical sense and serves primarily as a baseline for interpreting the other coefficients. 

* *Pvalue* - It is worth noting while there is strong evidence that the intercept differs from zero (pvalue = 0.001679 with $\alpha = 0.05$) it is not meaningful and not central to the research question.


**HeartRate**

* *Estimate* - For observations outside of 2023 (i.e., 2024–2026), each additional beat per minute in average daily heart rate is associated with approximately 133 additional steps per day, on average, holding all else constant. This represents the baseline heart rate–steps relationship.

* *Pvalue* - There is overwhelming evidence against the null hypothesis (pvalue = 1.027e-14 with $\alpha = 0.05$) that heart rate has no association with steps in the baseline period (2024–2026). This indicates a statistically significant positive relationship between average heart rate and daily steps outside of 2023.


**is_2023**

* *Estimate* - At a given heart rate, observations from 2023 are estimated to have about 22,000 more daily steps than observations from 2024–2026. This coefficient represents a shift in the intercept, indicating that <u>baseline activity levels in 2023 differ substantially from later years</u>. </BR></BR>Using the chart below as a visual, this large estimate may be due to a lack of heart rate data in 2023. In other words, only the data that have finite values for steps and heart rate can be plotted together on a scatterplot as well as be considered in a simple linear regression test. To qualify for a multiple linear regression test all data must also have a finite date value in the `Date` column. Fortunately that is not a worry as all dates are not null. But, in 2023 we see only the tail end of the year has heart rate data where several higher points for steps also lay. This means a bulk of 2023 steps data is discarded and does not influence these test results. Perhaps if more heart rate data had reliably been recorded for the earlier portion of 2023 this estimate would be much lower.

<!-- Plot: Red + Blue Scatterplot: Data Mismatch by year -->
